<div id="review_1973698784" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1973698784" />
    <a title="Richard Thompson" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/11657479-richard-thompson"><img alt="Richard Thompson" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1530711053p2/11657479.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1973698784?book_show_action=true">Apr 16, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Richard Thompson" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Richard Thompson" href="/user/show/11657479-richard-thompson">Richard Thompson</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/11657479-richard-thompson?shelf=sociology-and-anthropology">sociology-and-anthropology</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/11657479-richard-thompson?shelf=philosophy">philosophy</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1973698784" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5327743324320768806">For a long time I turned my nose up at Foucault based on what I thought that other people think that he says. It all seemed to be convoluted and beside the point, but he is so highly regarded that I decided that I should give him a chance to speak for himself, and I now confess that I was totally wrong. Foucault is brilliant. I don&apos;t always agree with him, and I think that some of his ideas need to be reexamined and evolved a bit in light of subsequent knowledge, but the core of his analysis is </span>
  <span id="freeText5327743324320768806" style="display:none">For a long time I turned my nose up at Foucault based on what I thought that other people think that he says. It all seemed to be convoluted and beside the point, but he is so highly regarded that I decided that I should give him a chance to speak for himself, and I now confess that I was totally wrong. Foucault is brilliant. I don't always agree with him, and I think that some of his ideas need to be reexamined and evolved a bit in light of subsequent knowledge, but the core of his analysis is insightful and smart. If Foucault had known, for example, about the studies of Zimbardo and Milgram, he might have approached some of his ideas from a somewhat different angle, but I think that he would still end up in more or less the same place.<br /><br />Foucault describes the history of discipline and punishment from the medieval world of the monastery and the inquisition to modern penitentiaries and ideas of deterrence and rehabilitation. He argues that throughout their history the varying systems of discipline and punishment can be best understood as different expressions of the modalities of power. As Foucault sees it, the systems evolved not to become kinder or more rational (although this may have been an incidental side effect), but to become more efficient and better able to serve the needs of those holding the levers of power in the modern world. The prison became the model for broader social mechanisms for discipline and punishment from the military to schools, hospitals and factories. These systems of organization and discipline became a key part of the mechanism of the industrial revolution and the modern world in general, which is only able to function effectively and achieve economies of scale by effective organization of masses of people. And a basic premise of all of this is that prison style mass organization can only work by objectifying the people who are cogs in the machine and is therefore a large scale violation of Kant's categorical imperative that we should always treat other people as ends not means. So the very thing that is the engine of our prosperity is antithetical to the Golden Rule. Foucault suggests that progress in science also comes out of this organizational paradigm although he never fully develops that part of his argument. Wow! No wonder a lot of people in the modern world are alienated and suicidal. It makes for depressing reading, but there's definitely something to it. <br /><br />But this is only a tiny part of what Foucault has to say. He has many more related insights which are developed in an engaging and accessibly written history of the penal system. There is a lot here to think about.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5327743324320768806" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

