  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3802321307" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3802321307" />
    <a title="Wiom biom" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/55748187-wiom-biom"><img alt="Wiom biom" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1608386569p2/55748187.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3802321307?book_show_action=true">Jul 25, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Wiom biom" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Wiom biom" href="/user/show/55748187-wiom-biom">Wiom biom</a>
      </span>

          added it




        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3802321307" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6050456344255366172">I really wanted to love this book. <br/><br/>Before reading Discipline and Punish, I had known a thing or two about Foucauldian thought and his genealogical writing, which I was fairly interested in since the impression I got was that it was a combination of history and philosophy. What I wanted to gain from reading this book was not just an understanding of the subject-matter itself (the birth of the prison) but also greater insight into Foucault&apos;s ideas, such as the relationship between power and knowle</span>
  <span id="freeText6050456344255366172" style="display:none">I really wanted to love this book. <br /><br />Before reading Discipline and Punish, I had known a thing or two about Foucauldian thought and his genealogical writing, which I was fairly interested in since the impression I got was that it was a combination of history and philosophy. What I wanted to gain from reading this book was not just an understanding of the subject-matter itself (the birth of the prison) but also greater insight into Foucault's ideas, such as the relationship between power and knowledge as well as his critique of normalisation. <br /><br />Yet, neither really materialised, though I am, now, inclined to add that perhaps this book is not meant for an uninitiated and careless reader like me, but for someone who is relatively well-acquainted with Foucault's ideas.<br /><br />For a start, the writing style simply did not work for me. It gave the impression of being overtly rhetorical so there was, in my opinion, more style than substance. That comes out, for instance, in the second last paragraph, where Foucault writes, "In this central and centralised humanity, the effect and instrument of complex power relations, bodies and forces subjected by multiple mechanisms of 'incarceration', objects for discourses that are in themselves elements for this strategy, we must hear the distant roar of battle." The distant roar of battle? I am not taking issue with the flowery language; Hobsbawm wrote expressively as well. I just think it would have been better for the reader if Foucault had been clearer and used the final pages to give a straightforward but comprehensive conclusion instead. Looking at that quote, I am reminded also of how difficult to read some sentences are; throughout the book, for example, sentences are littered with commas and sub-clauses. That certainly does not make it easier to comprehend his dense ideas and use of jargons. <br /><br />The various chapters are also written in an unfocused manner. For instance, the chapter on 'Illegalities and Delinquency' opens with a description of 'chain-gangs' instead of outlining the ideas he is about to present. Once again, this may be because I am not the ideal reader, but such sequencing made it horribly challenging for me to follow his argument. <br /><br />Content-wise, I do not dare to offer much criticism since I might end up transferring my failures onto the writer. Nonetheless, if one were to approach Discipline and Punish as a history book (which I know it isn't) then it isn't that good, primarily because Foucault draws generalisations from a limited range of sources from France, and occasionally from the US and the UK. I want to say that I learnt about the history of the prison but I don't think I did. <br /><br />It is disappointing that most of what I remember from the book is not his thesis but merely disparate pockets of insight regarding discipline, recidivism, etc. <br /><br />I guess I'll be reading other more accessible texts to clarify my understanding of this specific work as well as Foucault's ideas in general.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6050456344255366172" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

